Q. If I have a inheritance based scenario in which the parent is throwing one kind of exception
like one is throwing a IO Exception and the other is throwing custom exception. Both of them the
same method signature . Then what will happen in this case ?

Ans: 🔷 Scenario you described

     Parent class → method throws IOException
     Child class → same method throws custom exception

     👉 What happens?

     🔷 First Rule (VERY IMPORTANT)

     👉 In method overriding:

     Child class can only throw:

     ✔ Same exception
     ✔ Subclass of parent exception
     ❌ NOT a broader/new checked exception

     🔷 Case 1: Custom Exception is a subclass of IOException ✅

     class MyException extends IOException {}
     class Parent {
         void read() throws IOException {}
     }

     class Child extends Parent {
         void read() throws MyException {} // ✅ allowed
     }

     🧠 Why allowed?

     👉 Because:

     MyException is-a IOException
     So it follows Liskov Substitution Principle
     🔥 Output:

     ✔ Compiles successfully
     ✔ Works fine

     🔷 Case 2: Custom Exception is NOT related ❌

     class MyException extends Exception {}
     class Parent {
         void read() throws IOException {}
     }

     class Child extends Parent {
         void read() throws MyException {} // ❌ compile error
     }

     ❗ Why error?

     👉 Because:

     Parent says: “I may throw IOException”
     Child says: “I throw something else”

     👉 This breaks polymorphism

     💥 Compiler Error:
     Exception MyException is not compatible with throws clause in Parent.read()

     🔷 Case 3: Child throws NO exception ✅

     class Child extends Parent {
         void read() {} // ✅ allowed
     }

     👉 Child can reduce exceptions

     🔷 Case 4: Runtime Exception (Unchecked) ✅

     class MyRuntimeException extends RuntimeException {}
     class Child extends Parent {
         void read() throws MyRuntimeException {} // ✅ allowed
     }

     🧠 Why allowed?

     👉 Runtime exceptions are:

     -NOT checked by compiler
     -No restriction

     🔷 Summary Table

     Scenario	                                               Allowed?

     Same exception	                                           ✅
     Subclass exception	                                       ✅
     New checked exception	                                   ❌
     No exception	                                           ✅
     Runtime exception	                                       ✅

     🔷 Simple Rule to Remember

     👉
     Child can narrow exceptions, not widen them

     🔷 Real-life analogy

     Parent:

     “I may throw a File error”

     Child:

     ✔ “I throw a specific File error” → OK
     ❌ “I throw a Database error” → NOT OK

     🔷 🔥 Interview Answer
     👉
     In method overriding, the child class can only throw the same exception or its subclass if
     it is a checked exception. If the custom exception is not a subclass of the parent’s exception,
     it results in a compile-time error. However, unchecked exceptions can be thrown freely.